    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nCurrently the main instrument for retrieving syntactical information is tree-sitter which does support only context-free grammars. While usually this is enough, in some cases it isn't. For example, operators in Haskell have user-defined precedences and, with only tree-sitter, this information is just lost. Languages like Racket and Lean go even further: they allow arbitrary modifications to grammar which is just impossible to handle without external tools like compilers or languages servers (with language-specific extensions).\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nMy proposed solution is to create a general API for querying CST (something like `vim.syntax`) and use tree-sitter as the default fallback CST provider. In perspective, this API may also help with things like structural editing (#12842) and custom text objects (#8544).",
    "closed_at": "2026-05-31T06:58:17Z",
